/right-header-widgets -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /col-control -->\r\n\t</nav><!-- /nav -->\r\n\t\t<div id="wrapper" class="fix">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<div id="container" class="fix">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<div id="main-col">\r\n\t\t<div id="content" class="hfeed">\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-667 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-fedora category-hardware category-news category-security tag-centos tag-fedora tag-meltdown tag-redhat tag-security tag-spectre category-3-id category-109-id category-8-id category-14-id category-103-id post-seq-1 post-parity-odd meta-position-corners fix" id="post-667">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2018/spectre-meltdown-checker-in-fedora-and-epel-repositories/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'spectre-meltdown-checker in Fedora and EPEL repositories\' >spectre-meltdown-checker in Fedora and EPEL repositories</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/fedora/" rel="category tag">Fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/hardware/" rel="category tag">Hardware</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/news/" rel="category tag">News</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/security/" rel="category tag">Security</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2018/spectre-meltdown-checker-in-fedora-and-epel-repositories/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Feb</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">15</span><span class="year">2018</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2018-02-15T22:14:27+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>The recently disclosed <a href="https://spectreattack.com/">Spectre and Meltdown</a> CPU vulnerabilities are some of the most dramatic security issues in the recent computer history. Fortunately even six weeks after public disclosure sophisticated attacks exploiting these vulnerabilities are <a href="https://blog.fortinet.com/2018/01/30/the-exponential-growth-of-detected-malware-targeted-at-meltdown-and-spectre"> not yet common to observe</a>. Fortunately, because the hard- and software vendors are still stuggling to provide appropriate fixes.</p>\n<p>If you happen to run a Linux system, an excellent tool for tracking your vulnerability as well as the already active mitigation strategies is the <a href="https://github.com/speed47/spectre-meltdown-checker">spectre-meltdown-checker</a> script originally written and maintained by <a href="https://twitter.com/speedux">St\xe9phane Lesimple</a>.</p>\n<p>Within the last month I set myself the target to bring this script to Fedora and EPEL so it can be easily consumed by the Fedora, CentOS and RHEL users. Today it finally happend that the <tt>spectre-meltdown-checker</tt> package was added to the EPEL repositories after it is already available in the Fedora stable repositories since one week.</p>\n<p>On Fedora, all you need to do is:</p>\n<pre>\r\ndnf install spectre-meltdown-checker\r\n</pre>\n<p>After <a href="https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/EPEL#How_can_I_use_these_extra_packages.3F">enabling the EPEL repository</a> on CentOS this would be:</p>\n<pre>\r\nyum install spectre-meltdown-checker\r\n</pre>\n<p>The script, which should be run by the <tt>root</tt> user, will report:</p>\n<li style="list-style-type: none;">\n<ul>\n<li>If your processor is affected by the different variants of the Spectre and Meltdown vulnerabilities.</li>\n<li>If your processor microcode tries to mitigate the Spectre vulnerability or if you run a microcode which<br />\nis known to <a href="https://newsroom.intel.com/news/intel-security-issue-update-addressing-reboot-issues/">cause stability issues</a>.</li>\n<li>If your kernel implements the currently known mitigation strategies and if it was compiled with a compiler which is hardening it even more.</li>\n<li>And eventually if you&#8217;re (still) affected by some of the vulnerability variants.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<p>On my laptop this currently looks like this (Note, that I&#8217;m not running the latest stable Fedora kernel yet):</p>\n<pre>\r\n# spectre-meltdown-checker                                                                                                                                \r\nSpectre and Meltdown mitigation detection tool v0.33                                                                                                                      \r\n                                                                                                                                                                          \r\nChecking for vulnerabilities on current system                                       \r\nKernel is Linux 4.14.14-200.fc26.x86_64 #1 SMP Fri Jan 19 13:27:06 UTC 2018 x86_64   \r\nCPU is Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-5200U CPU @ 2.20GHz                                      \r\n                                                                                                                                                                          \r\nHardware check                            \r\n* Hardware support (CPU microcode) for mitigation techniques                         \r\n  * Indirect Branch Restricted Speculation (IBRS)                                    \r\n    * SPEC_CTRL MSR is available:  YES    \r\n    * CPU indicates IBRS capability:  YES  (SPEC_CTRL feature bit)                   \r\n  * Indirect Branch Prediction Barrier (IBPB)                                        \r\n    * PRED_CMD MSR is available:  YES     \r\n    * CPU indicates IBPB capability:  YES  (SPEC_CTRL feature bit)                   \r\n  * Single Thread Indirect Branch Predictors (STIBP)                                                                                                                      \r\n    * SPEC_CTRL MSR is available:  YES    \r\n    * CPU indicates STIBP capability:  YES                                           \r\n  * Enhanced IBRS (IBRS_ALL)              \r\n    * CPU indicates ARCH_CAPABILITIES MSR availability:  NO                          \r\n    * ARCH_CAPABILITIES MSR advertises IBRS_ALL capability:  NO                                                                                                           \r\n  * CPU explicitly indicates not being vulnerable to Meltdown (RDCL_NO):  UNKNOWN    \r\n  * CPU microcode is known to cause stability problems:  YES  (Intel CPU Family 6 Model 61 Stepping 4 with microcode 0x28)                                                \r\n                                          \r\nThe microcode your CPU is running on is known to cause instability problems,         \r\nsuch as intempestive reboots or random crashes.                                      \r\nYou are advised to either revert to a previous microcode version (that might not have\r\nthe mitigations for Spectre), or upgrade to a newer one if available.                \r\n\r\n* CPU vulnerability to the three speculative execution attacks variants\r\n  * Vulnerable to Variant 1:  YES \r\n  * Vulnerable to Variant 2:  YES \r\n  * Vulnerable to Variant 3:  YES \r\n\r\nCVE-2017-5753 [bounds check bypass] aka \'Spectre Variant 1\'\r\n* Mitigated according to the /sys interface:  NO  (kernel confirms your system is vulnerable)\r\n> STATUS:  VULNERABLE  (Vulnerable)\r\n\r\nCVE-2017-5715 [branch target injection] aka \'Spectre Variant 2\'\r\n* Mitigated according to the /sys interface:  YES  (kernel confirms that the mitigation is active)\r\n* Mitigation 1\r\n  * Kernel is compiled with IBRS/IBPB support:  NO \r\n  * Currently enabled features\r\n    * IBRS enabled for Kernel space:  NO \r\n    * IBRS enabled for User space:  NO \r\n    * IBPB enabled:  NO \r\n* Mitigation 2\r\n  * Kernel compiled with retpoline option:  YES \r\n  * Kernel compiled with a retpoline-aware compiler:  YES  (kernel reports full retpoline compilation)\r\n  * Retpoline enabled:  YES \r\n> STATUS:  NOT VULNERABLE  (Mitigation: Full generic retpoline)\r\n\r\nCVE-2017-5754 [rogue data cache load] aka \'Meltdown\' aka \'Variant 3\'\r\n* Mitigated according to the /sys interface:  YES  (kernel confirms that the mitigation is active)\r\n* Kernel supports Page Table Isolation (PTI):  YES \r\n* PTI enabled and active:  YES \r\n* Running as a Xen PV DomU:  NO \r\n> STATUS:  NOT VULNERABLE  (Mitigation: PTI)\r\n\r\nA false sense of security is worse than no security at all, see --disclaimer\r\n</pre>\n<p>The script also supports a mode which outputs the result as JSON, so that it can easily be parsed by any compliance or monitoring tool:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# spectre-meltdown-checker --batch json 2>/dev/null | jq\r\n[\r\n  {\r\n    "NAME": "SPECTRE VARIANT 1",\r\n    "CVE": "CVE-2017-5753",\r\n    "VULNERABLE": true,\r\n    "INFOS": "Vulnerable"\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    "NAME": "SPECTRE VARIANT 2",\r\n    "CVE": "CVE-2017-5715",\r\n    "VULNERABLE": false,\r\n    "INFOS": "Mitigation: Full generic retpoline"\r\n  },\r\n  {\r\n    "NAME": "MELTDOWN",\r\n    "CVE": "CVE-2017-5754",\r\n    "VULNERABLE": false,\r\n    "INFOS": "Mitigation: PTI"\r\n  }\r\n]\r\n</pre>\n<p>For those who are (still) using a Nagios-compatible monitoring system, <tt>spectre-meltdown-checker</tt> also supports to be run as <a href="https://exchange.nagios.org/directory/Addons/Monitoring-Agents/NRPE--2D-Nagios-Remote-Plugin-Executor/details">NRPE</a> check:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# spectre-meltdown-checker --batch nrpe 2>/dev/null ; echo $?\r\nVulnerable: CVE-2017-5753\r\n2\r\n</pre>\n<p>I just mailed to St\xe9phane and he will soon release version 0.35 with many new features and fixes. As soon as it will be released I&#8217;ll submit a package update, so that you&#8217;re always up to date with the latest developments.</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 22:14</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/centos/" rel="tag">centos</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/fedora/" rel="tag">fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/meltdown/" rel="tag">meltdown</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/redhat/" rel="tag">redhat</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/security/" rel="tag">security</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/spectre/" rel="tag">spectre</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-624 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-fedora category-open-source category-virtualization tag-container tag-fedora tag-lvm tag-lxc tag-lxd category-109-id category-15-id category-92-id post-seq-2 post-parity-even meta-position-corners fix" id="post-624">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/getting-started-with-lxd-on-fedora/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Getting started with LXD on Fedora\' >Getting started with LXD on Fedora</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/fedora/" rel="category tag">Fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/open-source/" rel="category tag">Open Source</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/virtualization/" rel="category tag">Virtualization</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/getting-started-with-lxd-on-fedora/#comments">2 Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Dec</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">20</span><span class="year">2016</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2016-12-20T18:30:01+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>Since a long time I&#8217;m using and following the development of the <a href="https://linuxcontainers.org/lxc/">LXC</a> (Linux Container) project. I feel that it unfortunately never really had the success it deserved and in the recent years new technologies such as <a href="https://www.docker.com/">Docker</a> and <a href="https://coreos.com/rkt/">rkt</a> pretty much redefined the common understanding of a container according to their own terms. Nonetheless LXC still claims its niche as full Linux operating system container solution especially suited for persistent <a href="http://rhelblog.redhat.com/2016/09/01/in-defense-of-the-pet-container-part-3-puppies-kittens-and-containers/">pet containers</a>, an area where the new players on the market are still in the <a href="http://blog.kubernetes.io/2016/12/kubernetes-1.5-supporting-production-workloads.html">stage of figuring out</a> how to implement this properly according to their concept. LXC development hasn&#8217;t stalled, quite the contrary, they extended the API with a HTTP REST interface (served via Linux Container Daemon, <a href="https://linuxcontainers.org/lxd">LXD</a>), implemented support for <a href="http://tycho.ws/blog/2015/04/lxd-live-migration.html">container live-migration</a>, added container <a href="https://insights.ubuntu.com/2016/04/01/lxd-2-0-image-management-512/">image management</a> and much more. This means that there are a lot of reasons why someone, including me, would want to use Linux containers and LXD.</p>\n<p><strong>Enable LXD COPR repository</strong><br />\nLXD is not officially packaged for Fedora. Therefore I spent the last few weeks by creating some community packages via their <a href="https://copr.fedorainfracloud.org">COPR</a> build system and repository service. Similar to the better known Ubuntu <a href="https://help.ubuntu.com/community/PPA">PPA</a> (Personal Package Archive) system, COPR provides a RPM package repository which can easily be consumed by Fedora users. To use the <a href="https://copr.fedorainfracloud.org/coprs/ganto/lxd/">LXD repository</a>, all you need to do is enabling it via <code>dnf</code>:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# dnf copr enable ganto/lxd\r\n</pre>\n<p>Please note that COPR packages are not reviewed by the Fedora package maintainers therefore you should only install packages where you trust the author. For this reason I also provide a <a href="https://github.com/ganto/copr-lxd">Github repository</a> with the RPM spec files, so that everyone could also build the RPMs on their own if they feel uncomfortable using the pre-built RPMs from the repository.</p>\n<p><strong>Install and start LXD</strong><br />\nLXD is split into multiple packages. The important ones are <code>lxd</code>, the Linux Container Daemon and <code>lxd-client</code>, the LXD client binary called <code>lxc</code>. Install them with:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# dnf install lxd lxd-client\r\n</pre>\n<p>Unfortunately I didn&#8217;t had time to figure out the correct SELinux labels for LXD yet, therefore you need to <a href="https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/SELinux_FAQ?rd=SELinux/FAQ#How_do_I_enable_or_disable_SELinux_.3F">disable SELinux</a> prior to starting the daemon. LXD supports <a href="http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/user_namespaces.7.html">user namespaces</a> to map the root user in a container to an unprivileged user ID on the container host. For this you need to assign an UID range on the host:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# echo "root:1000000:65536" >> /etc/subuid\r\n# echo "root:1000000:65536" >> /etc/subgid\r\n</pre>\n<p>If you don&#8217;t do this, user namespaces won&#8217;t be used which is indicated by a message such as:</p>\n<pre>\r\nlvl=warn msg="Error reading idmap" err="User \\"root\\" has no subuids."\r\nlvl=warn msg="Only privileged containers will be able to run"\r\n</pre>\n<p>Eventually start LXD with:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# systemctl start lxd.service\r\n</pre>\n<p><strong>LXD configuration</strong><br />\nLXD doesn&#8217;t have a configuration file. Configuration properties must be set and retrieved via client commands. <a href="https://github.com/lxc/lxd/blob/master/doc/configuration.md">Here</a> you can find a list of all supported configuration properties. Most tutorials will suggest to initially run <code>lxd init</code> which would generate a basic configuration. However there is only a limited set of configuration options available via this command and therefore I prefer to set the properties via LXD client. A normal user account can be used to manage LXD via client when it&#8217;s a member of the <code>lxd</code> POSIX group:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# usermod --append --groups lxd myuser\r\n</pre>\n<p>By default LXD will store its images and containers in directories under <em>/var/lib/lxd</em>. Alternatives storage back-ends such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_Volume_Manager_%28Linux%29">LVM</a>, <a href="https://btrfs.wiki.kernel.org">Btrfs</a> or <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZFS">ZFS</a> are available. Here I will show an example how to use LVM. Similar to the <a href="http://www.projectatomic.io/blog/2015/06/notes-on-fedora-centos-and-docker-storage-drivers/">recommended Docker setup</a> on Fedora it will use LVM thin volumes to store images and containers. First create a LVM thin pool. For this we still need some space available on the default volume group. Alternatively you can use a second disk with a dedicated volume group. Replace <code>vg00</code> with the volume group name you want to use:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# lvcreate --size 20G --type thin-pool --name lxd-pool vg00\r\n</pre>\n<p>Now we set this thin pool as storage back-end in LXD:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc config set storage.lvm_vg_name vg00\r\n$ lxc config set storage.lvm_thinpool_name lxd-pool\r\n</pre>\n<p>For each image which is downloaded LXD will create a thin volume storing the image. If a new container is instantiated a new writeable snapshot will be created from which you can create an image again or make further snapshots for fast roll-back. By default the container file system will be ext4. If you prefer <a href="http://oss.sgi.com/projects/xfs/">XFS</a>, it can be set with the following command:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc config set storage.lvm_fstype xfs\r\n</pre>\n<p>Also for networking various options are available. If you ran <code>lxd init</code>, you may have already created a <code>lxdbr0</code> network bridge. Otherwise I will show you how to manually create one in case you want a dedicated container bridge or attach LXD to an already existing bridge which would be configured through an external DHCP server.</p>\n<p>To create a dedicated network bridge where the traffic will be <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_address_translation">NAT</a>&#8216;ed to the outside, run:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc network create lxdbr0\r\n</pre>\n<p>This will create a bridge device with the given name and also start-up a dedicated instance of <a href="http://www.thekelleys.org.uk/dnsmasq/doc.html">dnsmasq</a> which will act as DNS and DHCP server for the container network.</p>\n<p>A big advantage of LXD in comparison to plain LXC is a feature called container profiles. There you can define settings which should be applied to a new container instance. In our case, we now want containers to use the network bridge created before or any other network bridge which was created independently. For this it will be added to the &#8220;default&#8221; profile which is applied by default when creating a new container:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc network attach-profile lxdbr0 default eth0\r\n</pre>\n<p>The <code>eth0</code> is the network device name which will be used inside the container. We could also add multiple network bridges or create multiple profiles (<code>lxc profile create newprofile</code>) with different network settings.</p>\n<p><strong>Create a container</strong><br />\nFinally we have the most important pieces together to launch a container. A container is always instantiated from an image. The LXC projects provides an image repository with a big number of prebuilt container images pre-configured under the remote name <code>images:</code>. The images are regular LXC containers created via upstream <code>lxc-create</code> script using the various distribution templates. To list the available images run:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc image list images:\r\n</pre>\n<p>If you found an image you want to run, it can be started as following. Of course in my example I will use a Fedora 24 container (unfortunately there are no Fedora 25 containers available yet, but I&#8217;m also <a href="https://github.com/lxc/lxc/issues/1356">working on that</a>):</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc launch images:fedora/24 my-fedora-container\r\n</pre>\n<p>With the following command you can create a console session into the container:</p>\n<pre>\r\n$ lxc exec my-fedora-container /bin/bash\r\n</pre>\n<p>I hope this short guide made you curious to try LXD on Fedora. I&#8217;m glad to hear some feedback via comments or <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/about/">Email</a> if you find this guide or the my <a href="https://copr.fedorainfracloud.org/coprs/ganto/lxd/">COPR repository</a> useful or if you have some corrections or found some issues.</p>\n<p><strong>Further reading</strong><br />\nIf you want to know more about how to use the individual features of LXD, I can recommend the how-to series of St\xe9phane Graber, one of the core developers of LXC/LXD:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/03/19/lxd-2-0-your-first-lxd-container-312/">LXD 2.0: Your first LXD container</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/03/26/lxd-2-0-resource-control-412/">LXD 2.0: Resource control</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/03/30/lxd-2-0-image-management-512/">LXD 2.0: Image management</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/04/12/lxd-2-0-remote-hosts-and-container-migration-612/">LXD 2.0: Remote hosts and container migration</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/04/13/lxd-2-0-docker-in-lxd-712/">LXD 2.0: Docker in LXD</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/04/14/lxd-2-0-lxd-in-lxd-812/">LXD 2.0: LXD in LXD</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/04/25/lxd-2-0-live-migration-912/">LXD 2.0: Live migration</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/10/26/lxd-2-0-lxd-and-openstack-1112/">LXD 2.0: LXD and OpenStack</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/04/18/lxd-api-direct-interaction/">Directly interacting with the LXD API</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/10/27/network-management-with-lxd-2-3/">Network management with LXD (2.3+)</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.stgraber.org/2016/12/07/running-snaps-in-lxd-containers/">Running snaps in LXD containers</a></li>\n</ul>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 18:30</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/container/" rel="tag">container</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/fedora/" rel="tag">fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/lvm/" rel="tag">lvm</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/lxc/" rel="tag">lxc</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/lxd/" rel="tag">lxd</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-596 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-open-source tag-ansible tag-dns category-3-id category-15-id post-seq-3 post-parity-odd meta-position-corners fix" id="post-596">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/managing-dns-zones-with-ansible/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Managing DNS zones with Ansible\' >Managing DNS zones with Ansible</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/open-source/" rel="category tag">Open Source</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/managing-dns-zones-with-ansible/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Sep</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">23</span><span class="year">2016</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2016-09-23T16:44:04+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>Currently, I&#8217;m working on automating the setup of a authoritative DNS server, namely <a href="http://gdnsd.org/">gdnsd</a>. There are many nice features in <code>gdnsd</code>, but what might be interesting for you, that it requires the zone data to be in the regular <a href="https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc1035.txt">RFC1035</a> compliant format. This is also true for <a href="https://www.isc.org/downloads/bind/">bind</a>, probably the most widely used DNS server, therefore the approach explained here, could be also used for <code>bind</code>. Again I wanted to use <a href="https://www.ansible.com/">Ansible</a> as automation framework, not only to setup and configure the service, but also to generate the DNS zone file. One reason for this is, because <code>gdnsd</code> doesn&#8217;t support zone transfers, therefore Ansible should be used as synchronization mechanism and because in my opinion the JSON-based inventory format is a simple, generic but very powerful data interface. Especially when considering the <a href="https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/intro_dynamic_inventory.html">dynamic inventory</a> feature of Ansible, one is completely free where and how to actually store the configuration data.</p>\n<p>There are already a number of Ansible <a href="https://galaxy.ansible.com/list#/roles?page=1&#038;page_size=10&#038;autocomplete=bind">bind roles</a> available, however they mostly use a very simple approach when it&#8217;s about configuring the zone file and its serial. When generating zone files with an automation tool the trickiest part is the handling of the serial number, which has to be increased on every zone update. I&#8217;d like to explain what solutions I implemented to solve this challenge.</p>\n<p><strong>Zone data generation must be idempotent</strong><br />\nOne strength of Ansible is, that it can be run over and over again and only ever changes something in the system if the current state is not as desired. In my context this means, that the zone file only needs to be updated if the zone data from the inventory has changed. Therefore, also the serial number only ever has to be updated in that case. But how to know if the data has changed?</p>\n<p>Using the powerful <a href="http://jinja.pocoo.org/">Jinja2</a> templating engine, I defined dictionary and assigned every value which would later go into the zone file. Then, I&#8217;ll create a checksum over the dictionary content and save it as comment into the zone file. If the checksum changed, the serial has to be updated. Otherwise the zone file includes the old serial and nothing changed. In practice this would look like this:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Read the hash and serial which are saved as comment in the existing zone file and register a temporary variable. It will be empty if the zone file doesn&#8217;t exist yet:\n<pre>\r\n- name: Read zone hash and serial\r\n  shell: \'grep "^; Hash:" /etc/gdnsd/zones/example.com || true\'\r\n  register: gdnsd__register_hash_and_serial\r\n  [...]\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Define a task which will update the zone file:\n<pre>\r\n- name: Generate forward zones\r\n  template:\r\n    src: \'etc/gdnsd/zones/forward_zone.j2\'\r\n    dest: \'/etc/gdnsd/zones/example.com\'\r\n    [...]\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>In the template, create a dictionary holding the zone data:\n<pre>\r\n{% set _zone_data = {} %}\r\n{% set _ = _zone_data.update({\'ttl\': item.ttl}) %}\r\n{% set _ = _zone_data.update({\'domain\': \'example.com\'}) %}\r\n[...]\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Create an intermediate variable <code>_hash_and_serial</code> holding the hash and serial read from the zone file before:\n<pre>\r\n{% set _hash_and_serial = gdnsd__register_hash_and_serial.stdout.split(\' \')[2:] %}\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Create a hash from the final <code>_zone_data</code> dictionary, compare it with the hash (first element) in <code>_hash_and_serial</code>. If the hashes are equal set the serial as read before (second element) in <code>_hash_and_serial</code>. Otherwise set a new serial which was previously saved in <code>gdnsd__fact_zone_serial</code> (see following section):\n<pre>\r\n{% set _zone = {\'hash\': _zone_data | string | hash(\'md5\')} %}\r\n{% if _hash_and_serial and _hash_and_serial[0] == _zone[\'hash\'] %}\r\n{%   set _ = _zone.update({\'serial\': _hash_and_serial[1]}) %}\r\n{% else %}\r\n{%   set _ = _zone.update({\'serial\': gdnsd__fact_zone_serial}) %}\r\n{% endif %}\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Safe the final hash and serial as comment to the zone file:\n<pre>\r\n; Hash: {{ _zone[\'hash\'] }} {{ _zone[\'serial\'] }}\r\n</pre>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Identical zone serial on distributed servers</strong><br />\nI didn&#8217;t explain yet, how <code>gdnsd__fact_zone_serial</code> is defined. Initially, I simply had <code>ansible_date_time.epoch</code>, which corresponds the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_time">Unix time</a>, assigned to the serial. This is the simplest way to make sure the serial is numerical and each zone update results in an increased value. However, in the introduction I also mentioned the issue of distributing the zone files between a set of DNS servers. Obviously, if they have the same zone data, they must also have the same serial.</p>\n<p>To make sure multiple servers are using the same serial for a zone update, the serial is not computed individually in each template task execution, but once for each playbook run. In Ansible, one can specify that a task must only run once, even the playbook is executed on multiple servers. Therefore I defined such a task to store the Unix time in the temporary fact <code>gdnsd__fact_zone_serial</code> which is used in the zone template on all servers:</p>\n<pre>\r\n- name: Generate serial\r\n  set_fact:\r\n    gdnsd__fact_zone_serial: \'{{ ansible_date_time.epoch }}\'\r\n  run_once: True\r\n</pre>\n<p>This approach is still not perfect. It won&#8217;t compare the two generated zone files between a set of servers. So you have to make sure that the zone data in the inventory is the same for all servers. Also, if you update the servers individually, the serial is generated twice and therefore are different, even when the zone data is identical. At the moment I can&#8217;t see any elegant approach to solve those issues. If you have some ideas, please let me know&#8230;</p>\n<p>The example code listed above is a simplified version of my real code. If you are interested in the entire role, have a look at <a href="https://github.com/ganto/ansible-gdnsd">github.com: ganto/ansible-gdnsd</a>. I hope this could give you some useful examples for using some of the more advanced Ansible features in a real-world scenario.</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 16:44</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/ansible/" rel="tag">ansible</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/dns/" rel="tag">dns</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-571 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-open-source category-security tag-ansible tag-apache tag-dovecot tag-letsencrypt tag-nginx tag-postfix tag-ssl category-3-id category-15-id category-103-id post-seq-4 post-parity-even meta-position-corners fix" id="post-571">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/lets-encrypt-with-acme-tiny/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'&#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; with acme-tiny\' >&#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; with acme-tiny</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/open-source/" rel="category tag">Open Source</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/security/" rel="category tag">Security</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/lets-encrypt-with-acme-tiny/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Sep</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">05</span><span class="year">2016</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2016-09-05T18:47:29+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>Most of my readers must have heard about the <a href="https://letsencrypt.org">&#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221;</a> public certificate authority (CA) by now. For those who haven&#8217;t: About two years ago, the Internet Security Research Group (ISRG), a public benefit group, supported by the <a href="https://www.eff.org/">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a> (EFF), the <a href="https://www.mozilla.org">Mozilla Foundation</a>, Cisco, <a href="https://www.akamai.com">Akamai</a>, the <a href="https://www.linuxfoundation.org/">Linux Foundation</a> and many more started the challenge to create a fully trusted public key infrastructure which can be used for free by everyone. Until then, the big commercial certificate authorities such as Comodo, Symantec, GlobalSign or GoDaddy dominated the market of SSL certificates which prevented a wide use of trusted encryption. The major goal of the ISRG is to increase the use of HTTPS for Web sites from then less than 40 percent two years ago to <a href="https://letsencrypt.org/2014/11/18/announcing-lets-encrypt.html">a 100 percent</a>. One step to achieve this, is by providing certificates to everyone for free and the other step, to do this in a fully automated way. For this reason a new protocol called <a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-acme-acme-03">Advanced Certificate Management Environment</a> (ACME) was designed and implemented. Going forward to today: The &#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; CA issued already more than five million certificates and the use of HTTPS is increasing to around 45 percent in June 2016.</p>\n<p><a href="https://github.com/diafygi/acme-tiny">acme-tiny</a> is a small Python script which can be used to submit the certificate request to the &#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; CA. If you&#8217;re eligible to request a certificate for this domain you instantly get the certificate back. As such a certificate is only valid for 90 days and the renewal process doesn&#8217;t need any user interaction it&#8217;s a perfect opportunity for a fully automated setup.</p>\n<p>Since a while I prefer <a href="https://ansible.com">Ansible</a> for all kind of automation tasks. &#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; finally allows me to secure new services, which I spontaneously decide to host on my server via sub-domains. To ease the initial setup and fully automate the renewal process, I wrote an Ansible role <a href="https://galaxy.ansible.com/ganto/acme_tiny/">ganto.acme_tiny</a>. It will run the following tasks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Generate a new RSA key if none is found for this domain</li>\n<li>Create a certificate signing request</li>\n<li>Submit the certificate signing request with help of <code>acme-tiny</code> to the &#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; CA</li>\n<li>Merge the received certificate with the issuing CA certificate to a certificate chain which then can be configured for various services</li>\n<li>Restart the affected service to load the new certificate</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In practice, this would look like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create a role variable file <em>/etc/ansible/vars/mail.linuxmonk.ch.yml</em>:<code><br />\nacme_tiny__domain: [ \'mail.linuxmonk.ch\', \'smtp.linuxmonk.ch\' ]<br />\nacme_tiny__cert_type: [ \'postfix\', \'dovecot\' ]<br />\n</code>\n</li>\n<li>Make sure the involved service configurations load the certificate and key from the correct location (see <a href="https://gantoacme-tiny.readthedocs.io/en/latest/system-configuration.html#service-configuration">ganto.acme_tiny: Service Configuration</a>).</li>\n<li>Run the playbook with the root user to do the initial setup:<br />\n<code><br />\n$ sudo ansible-playbook \\<br />\n-e @/etc/ansible/vars/mail.linuxmonk.ch.yml \\<br />\n/etc/ansible/playbooks/acme_tiny.yml<br />\n</code>\n</ul>\n<p>That&#8217;s it. Both SMTP and IMAP are now secured with help of a &#8220;Let&#8217;s encrypt&#8221; certificate. To setup automated certificate renewal I only have to add the executed command in a task scheduler such as <code>cron</code> from where it will be executed as unprivileged user <code>acmetiny</code> which was created during the initial playbook run. E.g. in <em>/etc/cron.d/acme_tiny</em>:</p>\n<pre>\r\nPATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/sbin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin\r\n\r\n@monthly acmetiny /usr/bin/ansible-playbook -e @/etc/ansible/vars/mail.linuxmonk.ch.yml /etc/ansible/playbooks/acme_tiny.yml >/dev/null\r\n</pre>\n<p>If you became curious and want to have a setup like this yourself, checkout the extensive documentation about the Ansible role at <a href="https://gantoacme-tiny.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html">Read the Docs: ganto.acme_tiny</a>.</p>\n<p>This small project was also a good opportunity for me, to integrate all the nice free software-as-a-service offers the Internet is providing for a (Ansible role) developer nowadays:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The code &#8220;project&#8221; is hosted and managed on <a href="https://github.com/ganto/ansible-acme_tiny">Github</a>.</li>\n<li>Every release and pull request is tested via the <a href="https://travis-ci.org/ganto/ansible-acme_tiny">Travis-CI</a> continuous integration platform. It makes use of the <a href="https://github.com/nickjj/rolespec">rolespec</a> Ansible role testing framework for which a small <a href="https://github.com/ganto/ansible-acme_tiny-test">test suite</a> has been written.</li>\n<li><a href="https://galaxy.ansible.com/ganto/acme_tiny/">Ansible Galaxy</a> is used as a repository for software distribution.</li>\n<li>The documentation is written in a pimped version of <a href="https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/">Markdown</a>, rendered via <a href="">Sphinx</a> and hosted on <a href="https://gantoacme-tiny.readthedocs.io/">Read the Docs</a> from where it can be accessed and downloaded in various formats.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>That&#8217;s convenient!</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 18:47</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/ansible/" rel="tag">ansible</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/apache/" rel="tag">apache</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/dovecot/" rel="tag">dovecot</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/letsencrypt/" rel="tag">letsencrypt</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/nginx/" rel="tag">nginx</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/postfix/" rel="tag">postfix</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/ssl/" rel="tag">ssl</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-547 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-linux tag-iproute2 tag-iptables tag-networking tag-routing category-3-id category-12-id post-seq-5 post-parity-odd meta-position-corners fix" id="post-547">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/policy-routing-on-linux-based-on-sender-mac-address/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Policy Routing on Linux based on Sender MAC Address\' >Policy Routing on Linux based on Sender MAC Address</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/" rel="category tag">GNU/Linux</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2016/policy-routing-on-linux-based-on-sender-mac-address/#comments">2 Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Apr</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">21</span><span class="year">2016</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2016-04-21T07:27:52+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>I recently had the task to setup and test a new Linux Internet\xa0<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateway_%28telecommunications%29">gateway</a> host as a replacement to an existing router. The setup is classical with some individual ports such as HTTP being forwarded with\xa0<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_address_translation#DNAT">DNAT</a> to some backend systems.</p>\n<div id="attachment_568" style="width: 480px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/policy-routing-1.png" rel="attachment wp-att-568"><img class="size-full wp-image-568" src="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/policy-routing-1.png" alt="Redundant router setup requiring policy routing" width="470" height="199" srcset="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/policy-routing-1.png 470w, https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/policy-routing-1-300x127.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 470px) 100vw, 470px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Redundant router setup requiring policy routing</p></div>\n<p>The new router, from now on I will call it router #2, should be tested and put into operation without downtime. Obviously this means that I had to run the two routers in parallel for a while. The backend systems however, only know one default gateway. Accessing a service through a forwarded port on router #2 resulted in a timeout, as the backend system sent the replies to the wrong gateway where they were dropped.</p>\n<p>Fortunately <a href="http://www.netfilter.org/projects/iptables">iptables</a> and <a href="http://www.linuxfoundation.org/collaborate/workgroups/networking/iproute2">iproute2</a> came to my rescue. They enable you to implement <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Policy-based_routing">policy routing</a> on Linux. This means that the routing decision is not (only) made based on the destination address of a packet as in regular routing, but additional rules are evaluated. In my case: Every connection opened through router #2 has to be replied via router #2.</p>\n<p>Using <code>iptables/iproute2</code> for this task this means: Incoming packets with the source MAC address from router #2 are marked with help of the <a href="http://ipset.netfilter.org/iptables-extensions.man.html#lbDE">iptables &#8216;mark&#8217;</a> extension. The <a href="http://ipset.netfilter.org/iptables-extensions.man.html#lbCS">iptables &#8216;connmark&#8217;</a> extension will then help to associate outgoing packets to the previously marked connection. Based on the mark of the outgoing packet a custom routing policy will set the default gateway to router #2. Easy, eh?</p>\n<p><strong>Configuration</strong><br />\nNow I&#8217;ll show some commands how this can be accomplished. The following commands assume that the iptables rule set is still empty and are for demonstration purpose only. Likely they have to be adjusted slightly in a real configuration.</p>\n<p>First the routing policy will be setup:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Define a custom routing table. There exist some default tables, so the custom entry shouldn&#8217;t overlap with those. For better understanding I will call it &#8216;router2&#8217;:\n<p><code># echo "200 router2" &gt;&gt; /etc/iproute2/rt_tables</code></li>\n<li>Add a rule to define the condition which packets should lookup the routing in the previously created table &#8216;router2&#8217;:<br />\n&amp;nbps;<br />\n<code># ip rule add fwmark 0x2 lookup router2</code></p>\n<p>This means that IP packets with the mark &#8216;2&#8217; will be routed according to the table &#8216;router2&#8217;.</li>\n<li>Set the default gateway in the &#8216;router2&#8217; table to the IP address of router #2 (e.g. 10.0.0.2):\n<p><code># ip route add default via 10.0.0.2 table router2</code></li>\n<li>To make sure the routing cache is rebuilt, it need to be flushed after changes:<br />\n<code># ip route flush cache</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Afterwards I had to make sure that the involved connections coming from router #2 are marked appropriately (above the mark &#8216;2&#8217; was used). The <a href="http://http://ipset.netfilter.org/iptables.man.html#lbAF">&#8216;mangle&#8217; table</a> is a part of the Linux iptables packet filter and meant for modifying network packets. This is the place where the packet markings will be set.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The first iptables rule will match all packets belonging to a new connection coming from router #2 and sets the previously defined mark &#8216;2&#8217;:\n<p><code># iptables --table mangle --append INPUT \\<br />\n--protocol tcp --dport 80 \\<br />\n--match state --state NEW \\<br />\n--match mac --mac-source 52:54:00:c2:a5:43 \\<br />\n! --source 10.0.0.0/24 \\<br />\n--jump MARK --set-mark 0x2</code></p>\n<p>The packets being marked are restricted to meet the following requirements:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>being sent by the network adapter of router #2 (<code>--mac-source</code>)</li>\n<li>don&#8217;t originate in the local network (<code>! --source</code>)</li>\n<li>target destination port 80 (<code>--dport</code>: example for the HTTP port being forwarded by router #2)</li>\n<li>belong to a new connection (<code>--state NEW</code>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Of course additional (or less) extensions can be used to filter the packets according to individual requirements.</li>\n<li>Next, the incoming packets are given to the &#8216;connmark&#8217; extension which will do the connection tracking of the marked connections:\n<p><code># iptables --table mangle --append INPUT \\<br />\n--jump CONNMARK --save-mark</code></li>\n<li>The packets which can be associated with an existing connection are also marked accordingly:\n<p><code># iptables --table mangle --append INPUT \\<br />\n--match state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED \\<br />\n--jump CONNMARK --restore-mark</code></li>\n<li>All the previous rules where required that the outgoing packets can finally be marked too:\n<p><code># iptables --table mangle --append OUTPUT \\<br />\n--jump CONNMARK --restore-mark</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Debugging</strong><br />\nThe following commands and iptables rules should help when setting up and/or debugging policy routing with marked packets:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>List policy of routing table &#8216;table2&#8217;:\n<p><code># ip route show table router2</code></li>\n<li>List defined routing tables:\n<p><code># cat /etc/iproute2/rt_tables</code></li>\n<li>Log marked incoming/outgoing packets to syslog:\n<p><code># iptables -A INPUT -m mark --mark 0x2 -j LOG<br />\n# iptables -A OUTPUT -m mark --mark 0x2 -j LOG</code></li>\n</ul>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 07:27</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/iproute2/" rel="tag">iproute2</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/iptables/" rel="tag">iptables</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/networking/" rel="tag">networking</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/routing/" rel="tag">routing</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-508 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-linux tag-ipmi tag-serial-terminal tag-supermicro category-12-id post-seq-6 post-parity-even meta-position-corners fix" id="post-508">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2015/setup-remote-server-management-of-a-supermicro-bmc-with-freeipmi-on-linux/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Setup remote server management of a SuperMicro BMC with FreeIPMI on Linux\' >Setup remote server management of a SuperMicro BMC with FreeIPMI on Linux</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/" rel="category tag">GNU/Linux</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2015/setup-remote-server-management-of-a-supermicro-bmc-with-freeipmi-on-linux/#comments">1 Response &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Dec</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">03</span><span class="year">2015</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2015-12-03T21:46:00+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p><a href="http://www.supermicro.com">SuperMicro</a> server mainboards often include a dedicated <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligent_Platform_Management_Interface#Baseboard_management_controller">Baseband Management Controller</a> (BMC) which offers out-of-band management of the server system. This is a dedicated embedded chip (<a href="http://www.supermicro.com/products/nfo/IPMI.cfm">Specifications</a>) which allow to power cycle the machine, monitor hardware variables, update firmware, access the operating system console and much more. If you are used to big brand server systems, then you might be more familiar with the term <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP_Integrated_Lights-Out">iLO</a>, which is the HP Integrated Lights-Out, or <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_Remote_Supervisor_Adapter#Integrated_Management_Module_.28IMM.29">IMM</a>, which is the IBM Integrated Management Module. The basic functionality is always comparable.</p>\n<h5>FreeIPMI Management Utility</h5>\n<p>A nice fact is, that most of these out-of-band management solutions support the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligent_Platform_Management_Interface">Intelligent Platform Management Interface</a> (IPMI) specification, which defines an interface for accessing the various functionalities from an operating system (OS) or the network (e.g. for monitoring or OS recovery). For Linux there exists GNU <a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/freeipmi/">FreeIPMI</a> which is a collection of powerful tools for accessing IPMI-compatible BMCs. It is available via default package manager on all major Linux distributions.</p>\n<p><strong>Linux Kernel Configuration</strong><br />\nAs mentioned before, on Linux there are two different ways to access the BMC via IPMI. The first way is directly from the host running on the board connected to the BMC. The connection is done via kernel modules. Make sure you have at least the <code>ipmi_defintf</code> and <code>ipmi_si</code> modules loaded. If your kernel doesn&#8217;t include this modules, you might need to add them to your kernel configuration. The corresponding settings can be found under:</p>\n<pre>Device Drivers ---&gt;\r\n   Character Devices ---&gt;\r\n      &lt;M&gt; IPMI top-level message handler ---&gt;\r\n          [ ]   Generate a panic event to all BMCs on a panic (NEW)\r\n          &lt;M&gt;   Device interface for IPMI (NEW)\r\n          &lt;M&gt;   IPMI System Interface handler (NEW)\r\n          &lt;M&gt;   IPMI SMBus handler (SSIF) (NEW)\r\n          &lt;M&gt;   IPMI Watchdog Timer (NEW)\r\n          &lt;M&gt;   IPMI Poweroff (NEW)\r\n</pre>\n<p>You can check if it&#8217;s working by invoking <code>ipmi-detect</code> which should then output something like this:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-locate\r\nProbing KCS device using DMIDECODE... done\r\nIPMI Version: 2.0\r\nIPMI locate driver: DMIDECODE\r\nIPMI interface: KCS\r\nBMC driver device: \r\nBMC I/O base address: 0xCA2\r\nRegister spacing: 1\r\n\r\nProbing SMIC device using DMIDECODE... FAILED\r\n\r\nProbing BT device using DMIDECODE... FAILED\r\n\r\nProbing SSIF device using DMIDECODE... FAILED\r\n\r\nProbing KCS device using SMBIOS... done\r\nIPMI Version: 2.0\r\nIPMI locate driver: SMBIOS\r\nIPMI interface: KCS\r\nBMC driver device: \r\nBMC I/O base address: 0xCA2\r\nRegister spacing: 1\r\n\r\nProbing SMIC device using SMBIOS... FAILED\r\n\r\nProbing BT device using SMBIOS... FAILED\r\n\r\nProbing SSIF device using SMBIOS... FAILED\r\n\r\n[...]\r\n</pre>\n<p>There was an IPMI 2.0 compatible chip found, so we are good to go.</p>\n<p><strong>Network Configuration</strong><br />\nThe second way to connect via IPMI to the BMC is over the network. For this, there often is a dedicated network port on the mainboard that obviously needs to be connected to a network switch over which you can access it. By default the SuperMicro BMC is configured to get an IP address via DHCP. If the local IPMI connection is working, you can get the IP address by executing:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-config --checkout --section Lan_Conf\r\n\r\n#\r\n# Section Lan_Conf Comments \r\n#\r\n# In the Lan_Conf section, typical networking configuration is setup. Most users \r\n# will choose to set "Static" for the "IP_Address_Source" and set the \r\n# appropriate "IP_Address", "MAC_Address", "Subnet_Mask", etc. for the machine. \r\n#\r\nSection Lan_Conf\r\n        ## Possible values: Unspecified/Static/Use_DHCP/Use_BIOS/Use_Others\r\n        IP_Address_Source                             Use_DHCP\r\n        ## Give valid IP address\r\n        IP_Address                                    192.168.1.15\r\n        ## Give valid MAC address\r\n        MAC_Address                                   0C:C4:7A:73:18:4F\r\n        ## Give valid Subnet Mask\r\n        Subnet_Mask                                   255.255.255.0\r\n        ## Give valid IP address\r\n        Default_Gateway_IP_Address                    192.168.1.1\r\n        ## Give valid MAC address\r\n        Default_Gateway_MAC_Address                   00:0D:B9:22:15:A2\r\n        ## Give valid IP address\r\n        Backup_Gateway_IP_Address                     0.0.0.0\r\n        ## Give valid MAC address\r\n        Backup_Gateway_MAC_Address                    00:00:00:00:00:00\r\nEndSection\r\n</pre>\n<p>Otherwise you might need to search the DHCP server log for an entry, which IP address was given to the BMC. I recommend to set the BMC IP address to a fixed value, to minimize the risk to loose connectivity in case of major data center issue. This can be done via Web interface at e.g. https://192.168.1.15 or via <code>ipmi-config</code>:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-config --commit -e Lan_Conf:IP_Address_Source=Static\r\n# ipmi-config --commit -e Lan_Conf:IP_Address=192.168.1.42\r\n</pre>\n<p>Alternatively you can write the configuration in file and commit it with the <code>--filename</code> argument. E.g. create a <i>static-network.conf</i>:</p>\n<pre># Static network configuration for the BMC\r\nSection Lan_Conf\r\n        IP_Address_Source                             Static\r\n        IP_Address                                    192.168.1.42\r\nEndSection\r\n</pre>\n<p>Unfortunately the <code>IP_Address_Source</code> key cannot be changed concurrently with other <code>Lan_Conf</code> keys. So we had to run the commit command twice, when specifying the new values on the command line and the same is true with the configuration file option. The first time it will set the <code>IP_Address_Source</code>:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-config --commit --filename=static-network.conf\r\n</pre>\n<p>And the second time, it will set the new <code>IP_address</code>:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-config --commit --filename=static-network.conf\r\n</pre>\n<p>However, this is an exception and most other key/value pairs can be changed concurrently. See the <a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/freeipmi/manpages/man8/ipmi-config.8.html">ipmi-config(8)</a> man-page for more details.</p>\n<p>Eventually we can check if the IPMI interface is reachable via network. This can be done with the <code>ipmi-ping</code> tool. If the <code>--verbose</code> argument is added, it will even output some information about the configured authentication settings. E.g.:</p>\n<pre># ipmi-ping --count 1 --verbose 192.168.1.42\r\nipmi-ping 192.168.1.42 (192.168.1.42)\r\nresponse received from 192.168.1.42: rq_seq=23, auth: none=clear md2=set md5=set password=set oem=clear anon=clear null=clear non-null=set user=clear permsg=clear \r\n--- ipmi-ping 192.168.1.42 statistics ---\r\n1 requests transmitted, 1 responses received in time, 0.0% packet loss\r\n</pre>\n<h5>Configure Serial-over-LAN (SoL) Console Access</h5>\n<p>A neat feature of a BMC is the ability to remotely access the Linux console even when the regular network connection to the server is not working any more. However, this needs some additional configuration in the operating system.</p>\n<p><strong>Check SoL Settings in BIOS</strong><br />\nFirst, we will check the BIOS settings to make sure the SoL feature is enabled. Note that accessing the BIOS usually already works in the default configuration, so if you are adventurous, you can already connect over remote IPMI (for demonstration purpose I&#8217;ll use the default user <code>ADMIN</code>):</p>\n<pre>$ ipmi-console -h 192.168.1.42 -u ADMIN -P\r\n</pre>\n<p>By default you won&#8217;t have access to the Linux system yet, so reboot the system via SSH so the BIOS can be setup accordingly. Unfortunately, the IPMI console won&#8217;t show the system&#8217;s POST output, so you have to keep pressing the <code>DEL</code> button in the terminal with the open IPMI console until you see the BIOS main screen. Then go to <code>Advanced -&gt; Serial Port Console Redirection</code> and make sure, the <code>SOL Console Redirection</code> is enabled. Also remember how many additional serial ports you have available for configuration in this menu. This will become important when selecting the correct console in the Linux configuration. E.g. my board only has one other serial port (COM1) available and for this one console redirection one mustn&#8217;t be enabled for SoL to work correctly.</p>\n<div id="attachment_542" style="width: 925px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SuperMicro_BIOS_SoL-Console-Redirection-Settings.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-542" src="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SuperMicro_BIOS_SoL-Console-Redirection-Settings.png" alt="SuperMicro BIOS settings accessed via ipmi-console" width="915" height="643" srcset="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SuperMicro_BIOS_SoL-Console-Redirection-Settings.png 915w, https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SuperMicro_BIOS_SoL-Console-Redirection-Settings-300x211.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 915px) 100vw, 915px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">SuperMicro BIOS settings accessed via ipmi-console</p></div>\n<p>If you want to see more verbose POST output, also disable <code>Quiet Boot</code> in the <code>Advanced -&gt; Boot Feature</code> menu.</p>\n<p>Leave the BIOS by pressing <code>Save Changes and Reset</code>. After a short while you should be greeted by the Grub menu. However, there won&#8217;t be any more output, as Linux doesn&#8217;t know yet, where to connect to the SoL console. To exit the IPMI console, you have to press <code>&amp;.</code>.</p>\n<p><strong>Setup Serial Console in Linux</strong><br />\nIf you have a systemd-based distribution all you need to do is to modify the kernel command line and add a serial console. Edit <i>/etc/default/grub</i> and extend the <code>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</code> variable as following:</p>\n<pre>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX="rd.lvm.lv=vg00/swap rd.lvm.lv=vg00/slash rhgb quiet console=tty0 console=ttyS1,115200n8"\r\n</pre>\n<p><strong>Important:</strong> This has to be <code>/dev/ttyS1</code> in case the BIOS knows only knows one additional serial port (which would correspond to <code>/dev/ttyS0</code>). If you have two additional serial ports in the BIOS (COM1/COM2), you must set <code>/dev/ttyS2</code> here. Don&#8217;t configure Grub 2 to output itself to the serial console, as this is still handled by the default SoL configuration forwarding the initial system output.</p>\n<p>Regenerate the <i>grub.cfg</i> with:</p>\n<pre># grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\r\n</pre>\n<p>You might need to adjust the command and <i>grub.cfg</i> path according to your installation. The next time when the system is booted, the Linux system output will be available on the serial terminal and there will also be a login prompt. If you don&#8217;t have a systemd-based system, you additionally need to enable the serial console login terminal in the <i>/etc/inittab</i>. E.g.:</p>\n<pre>T1:23:respawn:/sbin/getty -L ttyS1 115200 vt100\r\n</pre>\n<h5>Remotely Manage the System over IPMI</h5>\n<p>Now everything we need is in place. We can independently from the Linux operating system or the local system console:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Configure the BMC via <code>ipmi-config</code> (see above)</li>\n<li>Access the Linux console via <code>ipmi-console</code></li>\n<li>Query system sensor values (temperatures, voltages, &#8230;) via <code>ipmi-sensors</code></li>\n<li>Query system event log via <code>ipmi-sel</code></li>\n<li>Initiate system startup and power reset via <code>ipmi-power</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Even tough I have the latest available IPMI firmware installed, it sometimes happened to me, that the SoL wouldn&#8217;t properly connect to the Linux console any more after I disconnected when being in the BIOS. Or that I could navigate through the BIOS but it wouldn&#8217;t refresh the screen. Unfortunately the only way that I found to fix this, was to reboot the BMC. Of course also this is possible over IPMI:</p>\n<pre>$ bmc-device -h 192.168.1.42 -u ADMIN -P --cold-reset\r\n</pre>\n<p>There are many other things that you can do via IPMI. Also there are other tools which can access IPMI-enabled BMCs. Another famous one is <a href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/ipmitool/">ipmitool</a>. You might want to checkout Adam Sweet&#8217;s wiki on <a href="http://wiki.adamsweet.org/doku.php?id=ipmi_on_linux">IPMI on Linux</a> for more details how to use <code>ipmitool</code>. Personally, I prefer FreeIPMI for being a GNU project, being very intuitive to use and so far it worked perfectly well for everything I needed.</p>\n<p>If you have some hints or additions, please leave a comment below. Thanks for reading.</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 21:46</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/ipmi/" rel="tag">ipmi</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/serial-terminal/" rel="tag">serial terminal</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/supermicro/" rel="tag">SuperMicro</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-462 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-debian category-linux category-virtualization tag-debian tag-grub tag-kvm tag-mdadm tag-pygrub tag-raid tag-serial-terminal tag-virt-install tag-xen category-113-id category-12-id category-92-id post-seq-7 post-parity-odd meta-position-corners fix" id="post-462">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2015/migrate-32bit-physical-host-on-raid-1-to-kvmxen-virtual-machine/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Migrate 32bit physical host on RAID 1 to KVM/Xen virtual machine\' >Migrate 32bit physical host on RAID 1 to KVM/Xen virtual machine</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/debian/" rel="category tag">Debian</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/" rel="category tag">GNU/Linux</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/virtualization/" rel="category tag">Virtualization</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2015/migrate-32bit-physical-host-on-raid-1-to-kvmxen-virtual-machine/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Dec</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">01</span><span class="year">2015</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2015-12-01T01:52:07+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>I recently had the challenge to migrate a physical host running <a href="https://www.debian.org/">Debian</a>, installed on a ancient 32bit machine with a software RAID 1, to a virtual machine (VM). The migration should be as simple as possible so I decided to attach the original disks to the virtualization host and define a new VM which would boot from these disks. This doesn&#8217;t sound too complicated but it still included some steps which I was not so familiar with, so I write them down here for later reference. As an experiment I tried the migration on a KVM and a Xen host. </p>\n<h5>Prepare original host for virtualized environment</h5>\n<p><strong>Enable virtualized disk drivers</strong><br />\nThe host I wanted to migrate was running a Debian Jessie i686 installation on bare metal hardware. For booting it uses an <a href="https://wiki.debian.org/initramfs">initramfs</a> which loads the required disk controller drivers. By default the initramfs only includes the drivers for the current hardware, so the paravirtualization drivers for KVM (<code>virtio-blk</code>) or Xen (<code>xen-blkfront</code>) are missing. This can be changed by adjusting the <em>/etc/initramfs-tools/conf.d/driver-policy</em> file to state that not the currently dependent (<code>dep</code>) modules should be loaded, but <code>most</code>:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# Driver inclusion policy selected during installation\r\n# Note: this setting overrides the value set in the file\r\n# /etc/initramfs-tools/initramfs.conf\r\nMODULES=most\r\n</pre>\n<p>Afterwards the initramfs must be rebuilt by running the following command (adjust the kernel version according to the kernel you are running):</p>\n<pre>\r\n# dpkg-reconfigure linux-image-3.16.0-4-686-pae\r\n</pre>\n<p>Now the initramfs contains all required modules to successfully boot the host from a KVM virtio or a Xen blockfront disk device. This can be checked with:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# lsinitramfs /boot/initrd.img-3.16.0-4-686-pae | egrep -i "(xen|virtio).*blk.*\\.ko"\r\nlib/modules/3.16.0-4-686-pae/kernel/drivers/block/virtio_blk.ko\r\nlib/modules/3.16.0-4-686-pae/kernel/drivers/block/xen-blkback/xen-blkback.ko\r\nlib/modules/3.16.0-4-686-pae/kernel/drivers/block/xen-blkfront.ko\r\n</pre>\n<p><strong>Enable serial console</strong><br />\nTo easily access the server console from the virtualization host, it&#8217;s required to setup a serial console in the guest, which must be defined in <em>/etc/default/grub</em>:</p>\n<pre>\r\n[...]\r\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX="console=tty0 console=ttyS0,115200n8"\r\nGRUB_SERIAL_COMMAND="serial --unit=0 --speed=115200 --word=8 --parity=no --stop=1"\r\n[...]\r\n# Uncomment to disable graphical terminal (grub-pc only)\r\nGRUB_TERMINAL="console serial"\r\n</pre>\n<p>After regenerating the Grub configuration, the boot loader and local console will then also be accessible via <code>virsh console</code>:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg\r\n</pre>\n<h5>Run the host on a KVM hypervisor</h5>\n<p><a href="http://www.linux-kvm.org/page/Main_Page">KVM</a> is nowadays the de-facto default virtualization solution for running Linux on Linux and is very well integrated in all major distributions and a wide range of management tools. Therefore it&#8217;s really simple to boot the disks into a KVM VM:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Make sure the disks are not already assembled as md-device on the KVM host. I did this by uninstalling the <code>mdadm</code> utility.</li>\n<li>Run the following <code>virt-install</code> command to define and start the VM:\n<pre># virt-install --connect qemu:///system --name myhost --memory 1024 --vcpus 2 --cpu host --os-variant debian7 --arch i686 --import --disk /dev/disk/by-id/ata-WDC_WD10EFRX-68PJCN0_WD-WCC4J4527214 --disk /dev/disk/by-id/ata-WDC_WD10EFRX-68PJCN0_WD-WCC4J4366412 --network bridge=virbr0 --graphics=none</pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To avoid confusion with the disk enumeration of the KVM host kernel, the disk devices are given as unique device paths instead of e.g. <i>/dev/sdb</i> and <i>/dev/sdc</i>. This clearly identifies the two disk devices which will then be assembled to a RAID 1 by the guest kernel.</p>\n<h5>Run the host on a Xen hypervisor</h5>\n<p><a href="http://xenproject.org/">Xen</a> has been a topic in this blog a few times before as I&#8217;m still using it since its early days. After a long time of major code refactorings it also made huge steps forward within the last few years, so that nowadays it&#8217;s nearly as easy to setup as KVM and again well supported in the large distributions. Because its architecture is a bit different and Linux is not the only supported platform some things work not quite the same as under KVM. Let&#8217;s find out&#8230;</p>\n<p><strong>Prepare Xen Grub bootloader</strong><br />\nXen virtual machines can be booted in various different ways, also depending whether the guest disk is running on an emulated disk controller or as paravirtualized disk. In simple cases, this is done with help of <a href="http://wiki.xen.org/wiki/PyGrub">PyGrub</a> loading a Grub Legacy <i>grub.conf</i> or a Grub 2 <i>grub.cfg</i> from a guests <code>/boot</code> partition. As my <i>grub.cfg</i> and kernel is &#8220;hidden&#8221; in a RAID 1 a fully featured <a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/">Grub 2</a> is required. It is perfectly able to load its configuration from advanced disk setups such as RAID arrays, LVM volumes and more. With Xen such a setup is only possible when using a dedicated boot loader disk image which must be in the target architecture of the virtual machine. As I want to run a 32bit virtual machine, a <code>i386-xen</code> Grub 2 flavor needs to be compiled as basis for the boot loader image:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Clone the Grub 2 source code:\n<pre>$ git clone git://git.savannah.gnu.org/grub.git</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Configure and build the source code. I was running the following commands on a Gentoo Xen server without issues. On other distributions you might need to install some development packages first:\n<pre>$ cd grub\r\n$ ./autogen.sh\r\n$ ./configure --target=i386 --with-platform=xen\r\n$ make -j3</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Prepare a <i>grub.cfg</i> for the Grub image. The Grub 2 from the Debian guest host was installed on a mirrored boot disk called <i>/dev/md0</i> which was mounted to <i>/boot</i>. Therefore the Grub image must be hinted to load the actual configuration from there:\n<pre>\r\n# grub.cfg for Xen Grub image grub-md0-i386-xen.img\r\nnormal (md/0)/grub/grub.cfg</pre>\n</li>\n<li>Create the Grub image using the previously compiled Grub modules:\n<pre># grub-mkimage -O i386-xen -c grub.cfg -o /var/lib/libvirt/images/grub-md0-i386-xen.img -d ~user/grub/grub-core ~user/grub/grub-core/*.mod</pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A more generic guide about generating Xen Grub images can be found at <a href="https://blog.xenproject.org/2015/01/07/using-grub-2-as-a-bootloader-for-xen-pv-guests/">Using Grub 2 as a bootloader for Xen PV guests</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Define the virtual machine</strong><br />\n<code>virt-install</code> can also be used to import disk (images) as Xen virtual machines. This works perfectly fine for e.g. importing <a href="http://www.projectatomic.io/download/">Atomic Host</a> raw images, but unfortunately the setup now is a bit more complicated. It requires me to specify the custom Grub 2 image as guest kernel for which I couldn&#8217;t find a corresponding <a href="https://github.com/virt-manager/virt-manager/blob/v1.3.0/man/virt-install.pod">virt-install argument</a> (using v1.3.0). Therefore I first created a plain Xen <a href="http://xenbits.xen.org/docs/4.6-testing/man/xl.cfg.5.html">xl configuration file</a> and then converted it to a <a href="http://libvirt.org/">libvirt</a> XML file. The initial configuration <i>/etc/xen/myhost.cfg</i> looks as following:</p>\n<pre>\r\nname = "myhost"\r\nkernel = "/var/lib/libvirt/images/grub-md0-i386-xen.img"\r\nmemory = 1024\r\nvcpus = 2\r\nvif = [ \'bridge=virbr0\' ]\r\ndisk = [ \'/dev/disk/by-id/ata-WDC_WD10EFRX-68PJCN0_WD-WCC4J4527214,raw,xvda,rw\', \'/dev/disk/by-id/ata-WDC_WD10EFRX-68PJCN0_WD-WCC4J4366412,raw,xvdb,rw\' ]\r\n</pre>\n<p>Eventually this configuration can be converted to a libvirt domain XML with the following command:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# virsh domxml-from-native --format xen-xl --config /etc/xen/myhost.cfg > /etc/libvirt/libxl/myhost.xml\r\n# virsh --connect xen:/// define /etc/libvirt/libxl/myhost.xml\r\n</pre>\n<h5>Summary</h5>\n<p>At the end, I successfully converted the bare metal host to a KVM and/or Xen virtual machine. Once again Xen ended up being a bit more troublesome, but no nasty hacks were required and both configurations were quite straight forward. The boot loader setup for Xen could definitely be a bit simpler, but still it&#8217;s nice to see how well Grub 2 and Xen play together now. It&#8217;s also pleasing to see, that no virtualization specific configurations had to be made within the guest installation. The fact that the disk device names were changing from <i>/dev/sd[ab]</i> (bare metal) to <i>/dev/vd[ab]</i> (KVM) and <i>/dev/xvd[ab]</i> (Xen) was completely absorbed by the <a href="http://neil.brown.name/blog/mdadm">mdadm</a> layer, but even without software RAID the <i>/etc/fstab</i> entries are nowadays generated by the installers in a way, that such migrations are easy possible. </p>\n<p>Thanks for reading. If you have some comments, don&#8217;t hesitate to write a note below.</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span
