.post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-438 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-fedora category-open-source tag-apache tag-fedora tag-freeipa tag-kerberos tag-linux tag-redhat tag-ssl category-3-id category-109-id category-15-id post-seq-8 post-parity-even meta-position-corners fix" id="post-438">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/kerberized-http-auth-on-apache-mod_ssl-with-freeipa/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Kerberized HTTP Auth on Apache/mod_ssl with FreeIPA\' >Kerberized HTTP Auth on Apache/mod_ssl with FreeIPA</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/fedora/" rel="category tag">Fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/open-source/" rel="category tag">Open Source</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/kerberized-http-auth-on-apache-mod_ssl-with-freeipa/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">Aug</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">28</span><span class="year">2014</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2014-08-28T00:20:03+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>Today I just found out, how super easy it is to setup a safe HTTP authentication via Kerberos with help of <a href="http://www.freeipa.org" title="FreeIPA">FreeIPA</a>. Having the experience of managing a manually engineered <a href="http://kerberos.org/software/index.html" title="MIT Kerberos">MIT Kerberos</a>/<a href="http://www.openldap.org/" title="OpenLDAP">OpenLDAP</a>/<a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Create_a_Public_Key_Infrastructure_Using_the_easy-rsa_Scripts" title="EasyRSA">EasyRSA</a> infrastructure, I&#8217;m once again blown away by the simplicity and usability of FreeIPA. I&#8217;ll describe with only a few commands which can be run within less than 10 minutes how it&#8217;s possible to setup a fully featured Kerberos-authenticated Web server configuration. Prerequisite is a FreeIPA server (a simple guide for installation can be found for example <a href="http://inbaudwetrust.com/2014/02/12/freeipa-serverclient-setup-on-centos-6-5/" title="FreeIPA Server Installation">here</a>) and a RedHat-based Web server host (RHEL, CentOS, Fedora).</p>\n<p><strong>Required Packages:</strong><br />\nFirst we are going to install the required RPM packages:</p>\n<pre># yum install httpd mod_auth_kerb mod_ssl ipa-client</pre>\n<p><strong>Register the Web server host at FreeIPA:</strong><br />\nMake sure the Web server host is managed by FreeIPA:</p>\n<pre>ipa-client-install --domain=example.com --server=ipaserver.example.com --realm=EXAMPLE.COM --mkhomedir --hostname=webserver.example.com --configure-ssh --configure-sshd</pre>\n<p><strong>Create a HTTP Kerberos Principal and install the Keytab:</strong><br />\nThe Web server is identified in a Kerberos setup through a keytab, which has to be generated and installed on the Web server host. First make sure that you have a valid Kerberos ticket of a FreeIPA account with enough permissions (e.g. &#8216;admin&#8217;):</p>\n<pre># kinit admin\r\n# ipa-getkeytab -s ipaserver.example.com -p HTTP/webserver.example.com -k /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.keytab</pre>\n<p>This will create a HTTP service principal in the KDC and install the corresponding keytab in the Apache httpd configuration directory. Just make sure that it can be read by the httpd server account:</p>\n<pre># chown apache /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.keytab</pre>\n<p><strong>Create a SSL certificate</strong><br />\nNo need to fiddle around with OpenSSL. Requesting, signing and installing a SSL certificate with FreeIPA is one simple command:</p>\n<pre>\r\n# ipa-getcert request -k /etc/pki/tls/private/webserver.key -f /etc/pki/tls/certs/webserver.crt -K HTTP/webserver.example.com -g 3072</pre>\n<p>This will create a 3072 bit server key, generate a certificate request, send it to the FreeIPA <a href="http://pki.fedoraproject.org/wiki/PKI_Main_Page" title="Dogtag CA">Dogtag CA</a>, sign it and install the resulting PEM certificate on the Web server host.</p>\n<p><strong>Configure Apache HTTPS</strong><br />\nThe httpd setup is the only and last configuration which needs to be done manually. For HTTPS set the certificate paths in <code>/etc/httpd/conf.d/ssl.conf</code>:</p>\n<pre>\r\n[...]\r\nSSLCertificateFile /etc/pki/tls/certs/webserver.crt\r\nSSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/pki/tls/private/webserver.key\r\nSSLCertificateChainFile /etc/ipa/ca.crt\r\n</pre>\n<p>Additionally do some SSL stack hardening (you may also want to read <a href="https://www.insecure.ws/2013/10/11/ssltls-configuration-for-apache-mod_ssl/" title="SSL/TLS configuration for Apache mod_ssl">this</a>):</p>\n<pre>\r\n[...]\r\nSSLCompression off\r\nSSLProtocol all -SSLv2 -SSLv3 -TLSv1.0\r\nSSLHonorCipherOrder on\r\nSSLCipherSuite "EECDH+ECDSA+AESGCM EECDH+aRSA+AESGCM EECDH+ECDSA+SHA384 EECDH+ECDSA+SHA256 EECDH+aRSA+SHA384 EECDH+aRSA+SHA256 EECDH EDH+aRSA !aNULL !eNULL !LOW !3DES !MD5 !EXP !PSK !SRP !DSS !RC4"\r\n</pre>\n<p><strong>Kerberos HTTP Authentication:</strong><br />\nThe final httpd authentication settings for &#8216;<a href="http://modauthkerb.sourceforge.net/" title="mod_auth_kerb">mod_auth_kerb</a>&#8216; are done in <code>/etc/httpd/conf.d/auth_kerb.conf</code> or any vhost you want:</p>\n<pre>\r\n&lt;Location /&gt;\r\n  SSLRequireSSL\r\n  AuthType Kerberos\r\n  AuthName "Kerberos Login"\r\n  KrbMethodNegotiate On\r\n  KrbMethodK5Passwd On\r\n  KrbAuthRealms EXAMPLE.COM\r\n  Krb5KeyTab /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.keytab\r\n  require valid-user\r\n&lt;/Location&gt;\r\n</pre>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! After restarting the Web server you can login on https://webserver.example.com with your IPA accounts. If you don&#8217;t already have a valid Kerberos ticket in the Web client, <code>KrbMethodNegotiate On</code> enables interactive password authentication. </p>\n<p><strong>Troubleshooting</strong><br />\nIn case you get the following error message in the httpd error log, make sure the keytab exists and is readable by the httpd account (e.g. &#8216;apache&#8217;):</p>\n<pre>\r\n[Wed Aug 27 07:23:04 2014] [debug] src/mod_auth_kerb.c(646): [client 192.168.122.1] Trying to verify authenticity of KDC using principal HTTP/webserver.example.com@EXAMPLE.COM\r\n[Wed Aug 27 07:23:04 2014] [debug] src/mod_auth_kerb.c(689): [client 192.168.122.1] krb5_rd_req() failed when verifying KDC\r\n</pre>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 00:20</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/apache/" rel="tag">apache</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/fedora/" rel="tag">fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/freeipa/" rel="tag">freeipa</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/kerberos/" rel="tag">kerberos</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/linux/" rel="tag">linux</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/redhat/" rel="tag">redhat</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/ssl/" rel="tag">ssl</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-401 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-admin-hints category-fedora category-linux tag-apu tag-embedded tag-fedora tag-linux tag-pc-engines tag-serial-terminal category-3-id category-109-id category-12-id post-seq-9 post-parity-odd meta-position-corners fix" id="post-401">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/quickly-setup-a-fedora-19-boot-disk-for-serial-only-console-access/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Quickly setup a Fedora 19 boot disk for serial-only console access\' >Quickly setup a Fedora 19 boot disk for serial-only console access</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/admin-hints/" rel="category tag">Admin Hints</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/fedora/" rel="category tag">Fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/linux/" rel="category tag">GNU/Linux</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/quickly-setup-a-fedora-19-boot-disk-for-serial-only-console-access/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">May</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">16</span><span class="year">2014</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2014-05-16T00:01:11+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>I recently bought a <a title="PC Engines APU1C4" href="http://www.pcengines.ch/apu1c4.htm">PC Engines APU1C4</a> x86 embedded board which is meant to be the board for my future custom NAS box. In comparison to the various ARM boards it promises to be powerful and I/O friendly (3x Gbit LAN, SATA, 3x mini PCIe) and doesn&#8217;t include redundant graphics and sound circuits. On the other hand the only way to locally access it is via a serial terminal. Before installing the final system, hopefully more about this in a later article, I wanted to have a quick glance at the system from a Linux point of view. I tried booting the device over an USB stick prepared with my favorite live system <a title="SystemRescueCD" href="http://www.sysresccd.org">SystemRescueCD</a>, which by the way is based on <a title="Gentoo Linux" href="https://www.gentoo.org/">Gentoo</a>, but somehow failed as the boot process didn&#8217;t support output on a serial device and never spawned a terminal on it either. Before loosing too much time in searching for another media which would support a serial console, I simply setup my own minimal boot system based on <a title="Fedora" href="https://fedoraproject.org/">Fedora</a> 19. Here will follow a quick summary on what was required to achive this, as I couldn&#8217;t find a good and recent how-to about such a setup either. Because this minimal system is meant for ad-hoc booting only, I will keep things as simple as possible.</p>\n<p><strong>Prepare the installation medium</strong></p>\n<p>The APU1C4 supports booting over all possible storage devices, so you need to have a spare USB stick, external USB disk, mSATA disk, SATA disk or a SD card for storing the minimal Linux installation. Create at least one partition with a Linux file system of your choice on it and mount it. This will be the root directory of the new system. The following example will show how the setup is done on a device <code>/dev/sdb</code> with one partition mounted to <code>/mnt/usbdisk</code>:</p>\n<pre>host # mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/usbdisk</pre>\n<p><strong>Bootstrap minimal Fedora system in alternative root directory</strong></p>\n<p>Redhat-based distributions have an easy way to install a new system to an alternative root directory. Namely, it can be done with the main package manager yum. To keep it easy I used a Fedora 19 host system to setup the boot disk. While being in the context of the host system (below indicated with &#8216;<code>host #</code>&#8216;), always be careful that your commands are actually modifying the content under <code>/mnt/usbdisk</code>. Otherwise you might have a bad surprise when you reboot your host system the next time.</p>\n<p>1. Prepare RPM database:</p>\n<pre>host # mkdir -p /mnt/usbdisk/var/lib/rpm\r\nhost # rpm --root /mnt/usbdisk/var/lib/rpm --initdb</pre>\n<p>2. Install Fedora release package:</p>\n<pre>host # yumdownloader --destdir=/tmp fedora-release\r\nhost # rpm --root /mnt/usbdisk -ivh /tmp/fedora-release*rpm</pre>\n<p>3. Install a minimal set of packages (add whatever packages you&#8217;d like to have in the minimal system):</p>\n<pre>host # yum --installroot=/mnt/usbdisk install e2fsprogs kernel \\\r\nrpm yum grub2 openssh-client openssh-server passwd less rootfiles \\\r\nvim-minimal dhclient pciutils ethtool dmidecode</pre>\n<p>4. Copy DNS resolver configuration:</p>\n<pre>host # cp -p /etc/resolv.conf /mnt/usbdisk/etc</pre>\n<p>5. Mount pseudo file systems for chroot:</p>\n<pre>host # mount -t proc none /mnt/usbdisk/proc\r\nhost # mount -t sysfs none /mnt/usbdisk/sys\r\nhost # mount -o bind /dev /mnt/usbdisk/dev</pre>\n<p>5. chroot into the new system tree to finalize the installation:</p>\n<pre>host # chroot /mnt/usbdisk /bin/bash</pre>\n<p>6. Set root password</p>\n<pre>chroot # passwd</pre>\n<p>7. Prepare system configurations:</p>\n<pre>chroot # echo "NETWORKING=yes" &gt; /etc/sysconfig/network</pre>\n<p>8. If you only have one partition with the entire system, a fstab is not needed anymore as dracut and <a href="https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Systemd" title="Systemd">Systemd</a> will already know how to mount it. Otherwise create the fstab (use the UUID if you&#8217;re not sure how the disk will be called on the target system):</p>\n<pre>chroot # dumpe2fs -h /dev/sdb1 | grep UUID\r\ndumpe2fs 1.42.7 (21-Jan-2013)\r\nFilesystem UUID: bfb2fba1-774d-4cfc-a978-5f98701fe58a\r\nchroot # cat &lt;&lt; EOF &gt;&gt; /etc/fstab\r\nUUID=bfb2fba1-774d-4cfc-a978-5f98701fe58a / ext4 defaults 0 1\r\nEOF</pre>\n<p>9. Setup <a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/" title="Grub 2">Grub 2</a> for serial console:</p>\n<pre>chroot # cat &lt;&lt; EOF &gt;&gt; /etc/default/grub\r\nGRUB_DEFAULT=0\r\nGRUB_TIMEOUT=5\r\nGRUB_DISTRIBUTOR="Fedora"\r\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT=""\r\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX="console=ttyS0,115200n8 rd.lvm=0 rd.md=0 rd.dm=0 rd.luks=0 LANG=en_US.UTF-8 KEYTABLE=us"\r\nGRUB_TERMINAL="serial"\r\nGRUB_SERIAL_COMMAND="serial --unit=0 --speed=115200 --word=8 --parity=no --stop=1"\r\nGRUB_DISABLE_OS_PROBER=true\r\nEOF</pre>\n<pre>chroot # grub2-install /dev/sdb\r\nchroot # grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</pre>\n<p>10. We&#8217;re done. Exit the chroot and unmount it:</p>\n<pre>chroot # exit\r\nhost # umount /mnt/usbdisk/dev\r\nhost # umount /mnt/usbdisk/proc\r\nhost # umount /mnt/usbdisk/sys\r\nhost # umount /mnt/usbdisk</pre>\n<p>Now you can remove the disk from the host and connect it with the embedded board you want to boot.</p>\n<p><strong>Connect to the serial console and start the system</strong></p>\n<p>For connecting to the embedded board a USB to serial adapter and a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_modem" title="null modem">null modem</a> cable is required. There exist a number of tools to connect to a serial console on Linux which you probably already know (e.g. <a href="https://embeddedfreak.wordpress.com/2008/08/12/using-gnu-screen-to-debug-your-serial-port/" title="screen">screen</a> or <a href="https://alioth.debian.org/projects/minicom" title="minicom">minicom</a>). However, I always found them painful to use. The tool of my choice is called <a href="http://cutecom.sourceforge.net/" title="CuteCom">CuteCom</a> and is a graphical serial terminal. After selecting the correct serial device (<code>/dev/ttyUSB0</code> in my case) and baud rate, you can power on your device and you&#8217;ll hopefully be greeted by the boot messages of your board and the freshly installed Linux system:</p>\n<p><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/CuteCom.png"><img src="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/CuteCom-300x224.png" alt="CuteCom" width="300" height="224" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-414" srcset="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/CuteCom-300x224.png 300w, https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/CuteCom.png 912w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>\n<p>If there is no output in the terminal make sure, you use null-modem cable or adapter and not a simple serial extension cable. Further check for the correct serial port device in your serial terminal configuration and play around with the baud rate.</p>\n<p>Good luck and have fun with your embedded device. \U0001f642</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 00:01</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/apu/" rel="tag">APU</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/embedded/" rel="tag">embedded</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/fedora/" rel="tag">fedora</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/linux/" rel="tag">linux</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/pc-engines/" rel="tag">PC Engines</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/serial-terminal/" rel="tag">serial terminal</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- .post-footer -->\n\t</article><!--post -->\r\n\t<article class="full-content post-379 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-open-source category-webtipps tag-firefox tag-opensource tag-rss tag-tinytinyrss category-15-id category-21-id post-seq-10 post-parity-even meta-position-corners fix" id="post-379">\r\n<header class=\'post-header title-container fix\'>\n\t<div class="title">\n\t\t<h2 class="posttitle"><a href=\'https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/make-firefox-subscribe-rss-feeds-with-tinytinyrss/\' class=\'entry-title\' rel=\'bookmark\' title=\'Make Firefox subscribe RSS feeds with TinyTinyRSS\' >Make Firefox subscribe RSS feeds with TinyTinyRSS</a></h2>\n\t\t<div class="postdata fix">\n\t\t\t\t\t<span class="category"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/open-source/" rel="category tag">Open Source</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/category/webtipps/" rel="category tag">Webtipps</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="comments"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/2014/make-firefox-subscribe-rss-feeds-with-tinytinyrss/#respond">No Responses &#187;</a></span>\n\t\t\t\t</div><!-- /.postdata -->\n\t\t</div><!-- /.title -->\n\t\t<div class="date"><span class="month">May</span> <span\n\t\t\tclass="day">04</span><span class="year">2014</span></div>\n\t</header><!-- /.title-container -->\n\t<span class=\'post-format-icon\'>&nbsp;</span><span class=\'updated\' title=\'2014-05-04T02:00:23+00:00\'></span>\t<div class="entry-container fix">\r\n\t\t<div class="entry entry-content fix">\r\n<p>Since Google Reader shutdown its service in the middle of last year, <a title="Tiny Tiny RSS" href="http://tt-rss.org">Tiny Tiny RSS</a> is one of the better alternatives that one could use for aggregating and reading <a title="RSS" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rss">RSS</a> feeds. Next to the <a title="Tiny Tiny RSS App" href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.fox.ttrss">official Android app</a> which unfortunately isn&#8217;t free of charge, there is an alternative called <a title="TTRSS-Reader" href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.ttrssreader">TTRSS-Reader</a> which even supports offline synchronization. This combination makes me very happy. But one thing that bothered me since a while, was that subscribing to new feeds was very easy during the days of Google Reader. Today I finally figured out how to setup Firefox to automatically subscribe to a Tiny Tiny RSS instance.</p>\n<p>First go to the <code>about:config</code> page in your Firefox and search for the keys starting with <em>browser.contentHandlers</em>. Here we can configure a title and a URI which is later given as choice when subscribing to a feed. E.g:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>browser.contentHandlers.types.1.title</em>: My Tiny Tiny RSS</li>\n<li><em>browser.contentHandlers.types.1.type:</em> application/vnd.mozilla.maybe.feed</li>\n<li><em>browser.contentHandlers.types.1.uri: </em>URL of your TT-RSS instance<em><br />\n</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The <a title="Subscriber URL for TT-RSS" href="http://tt-rss.org/redmine/projects/tt-rss/wiki/FrequentlyAskedQuestions#I-need-a-URL-I-can-call-to-subscribe-to-feed-to-integrate-with-some-third-party-browser-extensionapplication">subscriber URL for TT-RSS</a> looks like the following. Of course you have to substitute the domain name with your domain:</p>\n<pre>https://example.com/ttrss/public.php?op=subscribe&amp;feed_url=%s</pre>\n<p>At the end, the Firefox configuration should look similar to this screenshot:</p>\n<p><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Firefox-RSS-aboutconfig1.png"><img src="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Firefox-RSS-aboutconfig1-300x185.png" alt="Firefox-RSS-about:config" width="300" height="185" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-393" srcset="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Firefox-RSS-aboutconfig1-300x185.png 300w, https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Firefox-RSS-aboutconfig1.png 917w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>\n<p>After the configuration is done, you have to restart Firefox. If you then browse to a Web site with a RSS feed and you click on it, the Firefox feed subscribtion page will appear. There you eventually can select the newly created entry for Tiny Tiny RSS:</p>\n<p><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Subscribe-feed.png"><img src="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Subscribe-feed-300x185.png" alt="Subscribe feed" width="300" height="185" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-395" srcset="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Subscribe-feed-300x185.png 300w, https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Subscribe-feed.png 915w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>\n<p>After selecting the entry, you&#8217;ll be redirected to your Tiny Tiny RSS instance, where you can configure the feed settings such as category and more.</p>\n<p>With this last piece of configuration, there is definitely nothing left anymore that makes me miss the time with Google Reader. \U0001f642</p>\n\t\t</div><!--entry -->\r\n\t</div><!-- .entry-container -->\r\n<footer class="post-footer postdata fix">\n<span class="author"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Posted by <span class="vcard"><a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/author/ganto/" class="url fn" rel="author">ganto</a></span> at 02:00</span>\t\t<span class="tags tax"><span class="icon">&nbsp;</span>Tagged with: <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/firefox/" rel="tag">firefox</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/opensource/" rel="tag">opensource</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/rss/" rel="tag">rss</a>, <a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/tinytinyrss/" rel="tag">tinytinyrss</a></span>\n\t</footer><!-- href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/wordpress/" class="tag-cloud-link tag-link-56 tag-link-position-43" style="font-size: 8pt;" aria-label="wordpress (1 item)">wordpress</a>\n<a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/wwdc/" class="tag-cloud-link tag-link-55 tag-link-position-44" style="font-size: 8pt;" aria-label="wwdc (1 item)">wwdc</a>\n<a href="https://linuxmonk.ch/wordpress/index.php/tag/xen/" class="tag-cloud-link tag-link-22 tag-link-position-45" style="font-size: 19pt;" aria-label="xen (6 items)">xen</a></div>\n</div></aside><!--widget end --><!--widget start --><aside id="categories-3" class="dbx-box suf-widget widget_categories"><div class="dbx-content"><h3 class="dbx-handle With 5.x after 5.6.28 or 7.x after 7.0.13, the issue is resolved in a non-default configuration with the opcache.validate_permission=1 setting. The vulnerability details are as follows. In PHP SAPIs where PHP interpreters share a common parent process, Zend OpCache creates a shared memory object owned by the common parent during initialization. Child PHP processes inherit the SHM descriptor, using it to cache and retrieve compiled script bytecode ("opcode" in PHP jargon). Cache keys vary depending on configuration, but filename is a central key component, and compiled opcode can generally be run if a script\'s filename is known or can be guessed. Many common shared-hosting configurations change EUID in child processes to enforce privilege separation among hosted users (for example using mod_ruid2 for the Apache HTTP Server, or php-fpm user settings). In these scenarios, the default Zend OpCache behavior defeats script file permissions by sharing a single SHM cache among all child PHP processes. PHP scripts often contain sensitive information: Think of CMS configurations where reading or running another user\'s script usually means gaining privileges to the CMS database.'}, u'CVE-2012-1823': With 5.x after 5.6.28 or 7.x after 7.0.13, the issue is resolved in a non-default configuration with the opcache.validate_permission=1 setting. The vulnerability details are as follows. In PHP SAPIs where PHP interpreters share a common parent process, Zend OpCache creates a shared memory object owned by the common parent during initialization. Child PHP processes inherit the SHM descriptor, using it to cache and retrieve compiled script bytecode ("opcode" in PHP jargon). Cache keys vary depending on configuration, but filename is a central key component, and compiled opcode can generally be run if a script\'s filename is known or can be guessed. Many common shared-hosting configurations change EUID in child processes to enforce privilege separation among hosted users (for example using mod_ruid2 for the Apache HTTP Server, or php-fpm user settings). In these scenarios, the default Zend OpCache behavior defeats script file permissions by sharing a single SHM cache among all child PHP processes. PHP scripts often contain sensitive information: Think of CMS configurations where reading or running another user\'s script usually means gaining privileges to the CMS database.'}, u'CVE-2012-1823': If the header value is not present in the charset conversion table, a fallback mechanism is used to truncate it to a two characters value to allow a quick retry (for example, 'en-US' is truncated to 'en'). A header value of less than two characters forces an out of bound write of one NUL byte to a memory location that is not part of the string. In the worst case, quite unlikely, the process would crash which could be used as a Denial of Service attack.
